ated names with similar meaning from other languages.","French: habitational name from Gray in Haute-Saône or Le Gray in Seine-Maritime."]},{"name":"Greiwe","meanings":["German: possibly a nickname from Middle High German <i>greibe</i> ‘sharp, tangy, dour’. Compare   Grey  ."]}]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705193,"age":6,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":51,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Henry de Grey was born in 1331, in Codnor, Derbyshire, England, his father, John de Grey, 3rd Baron Grey of Codnor, was 26 and his mother, Alice de l'Isle, was 22. He married Joan de Cobham before 1371, in Surrey, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died on 14 December 1392, in Derby, Derbyshire, England, at th